        title: 'A long-standing divide separates the church from the LGBTQ community',
        text: 'LGBTQ is a wide label that covers people who are not heterosexual or not cisgender. The group includes lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender, and queer individuals who question their sexuality. Across history these people have faced harsh persecution for how they live. Much of that persecution came from the church. Being gay or queer was treated as a crime against God and against the government. Father Martin uses his wide knowledge to find a way to bring this pushed-aside group back into the fold and keep them free of any condemnation. The church and its foundation frown on same-sex relationships, so the church has long been the last place an LGBTQ member wants to be. The church has stood at the front of the condemnation and has helped stir up the fires of persecution. Father Martin wants to close this divide or lay a bridge across it. Using the catechism and the life Jesus lived, he builds a template that readers can follow on how to relate better with LGBTQ people. Christ’s teachings show us how to treat the LGBTQ with greater care.\n\nIn today’s world there is more inclusion and many people are more open, yet LGBTQ members are still pressed down and persecuted. Much like bigotry, the church and its members have judged them as flawed and broken. Some feel they do not deserve God’s love. That notion will be broken apart as we read on.',
